[3
Date: Thu 15 Feb 2001 13:08:07
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Times of India 15 Feb 2001 [edited
<http://www.timesofindia.com/today/1hlth5.htm>

KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysia has banned imports of beef and livestock from
Thailand and Brazil because of fears about the spread of mad cow disease
[bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE, Health Minister Chua Jui Meng
announced on Wednesday [14 Feb 2001. The ban on Thai beef comes after news
from Thailand last week that 2 people were infected with a deadly human
variant of mad cow disease [new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, or
nvCJD, though the doctor at the source of the reports has since said that
he was misquoted and that the victims suffered from a different brain disease.
Malaysia's move on Brazilian beef products follows similar bans imposed by
the United States, Canada and Mexico on 6 Feb 2001. [There is currently no
evidence that BSE is in Brazil, but if the Canadians ban Brazilian beef
there must be a reason for it, even if not immediately scientifically
obvious. - Mod.MHJ Chua said that the bans were a precautionary measure;
Malaysian health officials had no official confirmation from Thailand that
humans had been infected with the disease.
He said Thailand may have been feeding its livestock with meat and bone
meal derived from cows imported from the European Union, where BSE has
broken out in several countries. He said beef products imported from
Thailand since 10 Feb 2001 and from Brazil since 6 Feb 2001 would be
recalled, and that security along the porous Malaysian-Thai border would be
stepped up to check smuggling of livestock into the country.
Malaysia barred beef and beef products from the EU and Switzerland on 5 Jan
2001. "We will continue with the ban until we get an assurance that there
is no danger to consumers from eating beef and beef products from these
countries," Chua told a news conference.
The latest measures would have minimal effect on the availability of beef
in Malaysia, which imports most of its beef from India, Australia, and New
Zealand, Chua said. Malaysia imported more than 400 million ringgits (US
$105 million) of beef and beef products last year, 193 000 ringgits (US $51
000) of which came from Thailand.
